Theorem: For all natural numbers n, if n is odd then 
\begin_inset Formula $n^2 + 2n$
\end_inset

 is odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Direct Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

It can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $n^2$
\end_inset

 is odd (for odd n), and 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 is even, and that the operation 
\begin_inset Formula $odd + even$
\end_inset

 always produces odd output.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Proof by contradiction (
\begin_inset Formula $n^2$
\end_inset

 is odd, for odd n):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $n^2 $
\end_inset

 is even, for odd n, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n^2 $
\end_inset

 is divisible by only one even number, 2. It follows that if 
\begin_inset Formula $n^2$
\end_inset

 is divisible by 2, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 must be divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

, a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $n \in \mathbb{N}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Direct proof(
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 is even):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

For any choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

, is divisible by 2. Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 is even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Direct proof (
\begin_inset Formula $even + odd = odd$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

For some numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b \in \mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

